4. Protocol Specification

The protocol implements the mathematics into a layered, cryptographically secured system. The design principles are unchanged from Version 2.0, but we emphasize the mapping to mathematical objects and the use of RG invariance.

4.1 Design Principles

· Minimality – only essential rules are fixed.
· Universality – same protocol applies at every scale.
· Immutability of Core – invariant rules resist capture.
· Extensibility – higher‑level diversity is free.

4.2 Protocol Stack

Layer Function Mathematical Correspondence
L0 – Identity Self‑sovereign identity, Sybil resistance Node identification, costs
L1 – Consent & Delegation Dynamic delegation, aggregated consent Delegation weights d_{u\to v}, non‑linear aggregation f
L2 – Decision Proposal format, consensus, action Governance function \Phi_v
L3 – Feedback & Audit Metrics, auditability, dispute resolution Error term \eta, stability condition
L4 – Meta‑Protocol Controlled evolution of the protocol itself Fixed‑point condition for protocol updates, RG invariance

4.3 Invariant Protocol Rules (Core)

These rules correspond to the fixed‑point constraints and ensure the Hamiltonian is at the RG fixed point:

1. Individual Sovereignty – \forall v \in L_0: \mathcal{L}(v) = \text{intrinsic}.
2. No Unilateral Change – No single node or layer may alter the core protocol.
3. Recursive Consent – Protocol upgrades require approval from at least two adjacent scales.
4. Rights Invariance – Fundamental rights (bodily autonomy, freedom of association, cognitive liberty) are immutable.

