5. Adversarial Model and Game‑Theoretic Analysis

5.1 Agent Utility

Each node v seeks to maximize:

U_v = B_v - C_v + I_v,
\]  

where B_v are benefits from favorable outcomes, C_v are costs (including participation and identity costs), and I_v is influence.

5.2 Threat Model with Phase Transition Perspective

We classify attacks and now connect them to the phase transition framework:

Attack Target Resilience Condition Phase Transition Effect
Sybil L0 – Identity Identity cost > benefit of fake identity Increases noise, can push system out of criticality
Collusion L1 – Delegation Delegation entropy H \ge H_{\min} Creates long‑range correlations, driving toward authoritarian phase
Protocol Capture L4 – Meta‑Protocol Multi‑scale approval + time delay Changes RG fixed point, leading to instability
Feedback Manipulation L3 – Feedback Multi‑source consensus + slashing Distorts information flow, reduces mutual information

5.3 Byzantine Resilience Across Layers

Theorem 7 (Resilience Threshold).
Let the decision rule at layer L_{i+1} require a supermajority q > 1/2 of the aggregated consent (e.g., q = 2/3 for Byzantine fault tolerance). If the fraction of malicious nodes in L_i satisfies

\lambda < \frac{q - 1/2}{1 - 1/2} = 2q - 1,
\]  

then honest nodes can ensure that the aggregated signal sent to L_{i+1} reflects the true majority of honest consent.

For q=2/3, we require \lambda < 1/3. This bound propagates recursively.

5.4 Delegation Entropy Constraint

H = -\sum_{v \in L_i} p_v \log p_v \ge H_{\min}, \quad p_v = \frac{c_v}{\sum_{w} c_w}.
\]  

Lemma 3 (Collusion Deterrence).
If H_{\min} is set sufficiently high, any coalition that attempts to concentrate influence will violate the entropy constraint, triggering automatic redistribution.

5.5 Slashing Condition for Feedback Manipulation

Definition 8 (Slashing).
Let \text{fb}_v be the feedback provided by node v, and let \overline{\text{fb}}_v be the median of feedback from its neighbours. Define a penalty

\Psi_v = \begin{cases}
0 & \text{if } |\text{fb}_v - \overline{\text{fb}}_v| \le \epsilon, \\
\kappa \cdot (|\text{fb}_v - \overline{\text{fb}}_v| - \epsilon) & \text{otherwise}.
\end{cases}
\]  

Lemma 4 (Honest Feedback as Dominant Strategy).
If \Psi_v > \Delta U_v for all v, where \Delta U_v is the maximum possible gain from lying, then truthful feedback is a dominant strategy.

5.6 Coalition‑Proof Equilibrium

Definition 9 (Coalition‑Proof Equilibrium).
A strategy profile is a CPE if no coalition can deviate and make all its members strictly better off, considering that the coalition’s deviation is itself a Nash equilibrium in the induced subgame.

Theorem 8 (Honest Participation as CPE).
Under the protocol constraints (identity cost, delegation entropy, core rigidity, multi‑source feedback), the strategy profile where every node delegates according to true preferences and follows the protocol is a coalition‑proof equilibrium.

Proof sketch. As in Version 2.0, with added observation that any deviation that attempts to create a phase transition (e.g., collusion to create long‑range order) will be countered by the entropy constraint and slashing. ∎

5.7 Mechanism Design and Incentive Compatibility

Lemma 5 (Incentive Compatibility).
If the slashing condition holds and the decision rule is monotonic, then truthful reporting is a dominant strategy in the delegation and voting stages.

Corollary 3 (Subgame Perfect Equilibrium).
By the revelation principle, there exists an equivalent mechanism that implements the desired outcome in subgame‑perfect equilibrium.

